<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-03-13T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-03-13T20:00:00-05:00" n="438" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d438">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.7962/112a: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wharton</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-13T21:00:00-04:00">March 13,
                                    1942—9 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>54. For McBride. Please telegraph what measures can in your opinion be
                            taken to exercise censorship in Liberia regarding present <pb facs="0381" n="369" xml:id="pg_369"/> and future plans and
                            operations of American forces, including particularly activities at the
                            airport. War Department understands that Associated Press maintains a
                            correspondent in Monrovia, believed to be the wife of a Firestone
                            employee.</p>
                        <p>You may in your discretion discuss this subject with President
                            Barclay.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>